fordshire, England","Wrentham, Suffolk, , England":"Wrentham, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1138–1189":"1138–1189","1125–Male":"1125–Deceased","1142–1192":"1142–1192","1135–Female":"1135–Deceased","1150–Male":"1150–Deceased","1162–Male":"1162–Deceased","1164–1218":"1164–1218","–Male":"Deceased","1096–1149":"1096–1149","1100–Female":"1100–Deceased","about 1150":"about 1150","about 1162":"about 1162","1164":"1164","1142":"1142","1096":"1096","1162":"1162","1150":"1150","1192":"1192","1138":"1138","1149":"1149","1125":"1125","1135":"1135","1189":"1189","1100":"1100","1218":"1218","Banbury, Oxfordshire, England":"Banbury, Oxfordshire, England","Wrentham, Suffolk, England":"Wrentham, Suffolk, England","Oscray Abbey, England":"Abbey, Devon, England","England":"England","Hook Norton, Oxfordshire, England":"Hook Norton, Oxfordshire, England","Wrentham, Suffolk, , England":"Wrentham, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"d'Oyley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Olley   with fused Old French preposition <i>d'</i> ‘from’."],"variants":[{"name":"Olley","meanings":["English (East Anglia): variant of   Oley   2, a habitational name of Norman origin, from any of the five places called Ouilly in Calvados, France."]},{"name":"Dilley","meanings":["English: possibly a pet form of an unrecorded Old English personal name <i>Dylla</i>, found as the first element in the placenames Dillington (in the former Huntingdonshire) and Dilton (in Wiltshire). The name may sometimes have been confused with   Doyley   and   Dolley   (see   Olley  ).","German: variant of   Dilly   or a surname of French origin, an altered form of   Delay  .","In some cases also an altered form of French   Dilly  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Gilbert d'Oyley was born in 1138, in Hook Norton, Oxfordshire, England, his father, Gilbert d'Oilly the Younger, was 43 and his mother, Mrs. Gilbert d'Oilly, was 38. He had at least 4 sons with Agnes De Grey. He died in 1189, in Wrentham, Suffolk, England, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1138–1189":"1138–1189","1125–Male":"1125–Surnud","1142–1192":"1142–1192","1135–Female":"1135–Surnud","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1162–Male":"1162–Surnud","1164–1218":"1164–1218","–Male":"Surnud","1096–1149":"1096–1149","1100–Female":"